{"cursor":"7499","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'solid solution' is a solid-state solution of one or more solutes in a\nsolvent. Such a mixture is considered a solution rather than a compound when the\ncrystal structure of the solvent remains unchanged by addition of the solutes,\nand when the mixture remains in a single homogeneous phase. This often happens\nwhen the two elements (generally metals) involved are close together on the\nperiodic table; conversely, a chemical compound is generally a result of the non-\nproximity of the two metals involved on the periodic table.\n","linknr":245,"url":"Solid_solution","recorded":1362486013,"links":38,"instances":["chemistry","materials","matter"],"pdf":["http://www.uni-graz.at/IEC-7/PDF-files/Chen.pdf","http://www.uni-graz.at/IEC-7/PDF-files/Chen.pdf","http://www.mines.utah.edu/~wmep/59298/592PDF/rlm2.pdf","http://www.mines.utah.edu/~wmep/59298/592PDF/rlm2.pdf"],"categories":["Materials science","Mineralogy"],"headings":["Details","Application","Exsolution","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Solid_solution.svg/200px-Solid_solution.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Eutektikum_new.svg/250px-Eutektikum_new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/7/1/071997f13634882f823041b057f90923.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/f/c/7fc56270e7a70fa81a5935b72eacbe29.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/5/9d5ed678fe57bcca610140957afab571.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/5/9d5ed678fe57bcca610140957afab571.png","//up